    "body": "Neovim has developed much over the past few years. But there was always one thing that I wished Neovim was which Neovim currently isn't, and that is being an X11 window manager. Now you might say that a text editor shouldn't be a window manager, but to that, I say Neovim already does other things that text editors shouldn't be (like `vim.system`).\r\n\r\n**Why would anyone use it over other X11 window managers?**\r\nThere are multiple reasons to use Neovim as a window manager. One of the main reasons is that you can create your tiling layout (or other window management script) by positioning Vim windows using VimL or Nvim-Lua without needing to learn a single bit of X11.\r\n\r\n**Why not Wayland?**\r\nBecause Wayland is hard.\r\n\r\n**Why write it in Lua instead of C?**\r\nBecause I don't know a lot of the internal Neovim C functions. (If required, I can rewrite it in C)\r\n\r\n**It uses LuaJit-FFI, and LuaJit is not a target**\r\nLet's make an exception. And for those who can't have Neovim running with LuaJit because they can't compile LuaJit to that hardware, I am pretty sure that they also can't compile an X11 server on that hardware.\r\n\r\n**TODO**\r\n+ [ ] Floating Vim windows\r\n+ [ ] Documentation\r\n+ [ ] Testing",
